    ("""Chelsea flourished during the 1960s, embodying the glamour and style of Swinging London. Under manager Tommy Docherty, the club reached the FA Cup Final in 1965 but lost to Leicester City after a replay. The squad featured exciting young talents including Terry Venables, Bobby Tambling — still Chelsea's all-time leading scorer in terms of competitive goals at the time — and Peter Bonetti, the elegant goalkeeper nicknamed 'The Cat'. Dave Sexton took over as manager in 1967 and guided Chelsea to their second FA Cup title in 1970, defeating Leeds United in a replay at Old Trafford after a ferocious first match at Wembley ended 2–2. The following year, 1971, Chelsea claimed the UEFA Cup Winners' Cup, beating Real Madrid 2–1 in a replay in Athens. This made Chelsea one of the few English clubs to hold a major European trophy. The squad during this golden period included Charlie Cooke, Alan Hudson, Peter Osgood — known as 'The King of Stamford Bridge' — and John Hollins.""", None),

    ("4. DECLINE AND FINANCIAL CRISIS (1975–1993)", None),
