    ("12. CLUB IDENTITY, COLOURS, AND BADGE", None),
    ("""Chelsea play in royal blue shirts with white shorts, a colour scheme that has been the club's primary identity since the 1960s. Earlier kits featured lighter blue shades. Away kits have varied significantly over the years. The club crest has evolved four times: the original 1905 badge depicted a Chelsea Pensioner; a second badge introduced in 1952 featured initials; the third and most iconic version featured a rampant lion holding a staff — derived from the coat of arms of Earl Cadogan, who was club president — and this lion symbol remains central to the identity today. The current badge, redesigned in 2005 for the centenary, retains the lion motif in a more modern, stylised form with 'CFC' lettering. The club's motto, printed on the badge, is 'Nisi Dominus Frustra' — Latin for 'Unless the Lord, in vain', taken from Psalm 127.""", None),
